Unrestrained Central Bankers?
Prague — Recently, one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries has become fashionable.
The main points of criticism are roughly as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their authority has expanded too quickly, and they are harming the economy.
This argument — strangely, it is popular among ideologically incompatible camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists — is completely wrong.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are not only responsible for curbing inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
The price level is like a person's body temperature, which can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing serious symptoms.
When combating deflation caused by weak demand and curbing high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "active".
Although the battle is entirely symmetric, the public's assessment of it is strangely biased, especially in countries where people are financially very conservative.
This includes my homeland, the Czech Republic. Czech savers save very little, and the loan-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs are concerned about inflation, even though the inflation rate in the Czech Republic reached a 13-year low last year, and since 2013, when I have served as the deputy governor, the Czech National Bank has been committed to eliminating deflation risks.
Other common complaints about the policies of central banks in developed countries since 2008 is that these policies have caused redistribution effects.
Of course they do, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while cutting interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong currency; exporters prefer a weak currency.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; it is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks have failed to meet inflation targets in any case, and therefore their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even put these contradictory criticisms into one sentence, as if they were accusing someone of shooting blanks yet causing casualties.
The reality is that central banks around the world have successfully maintained price stability and the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis — and it was an undeniable tremendous success.
Without their intervention, their economies would have faced catastrophic deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a complete collapse of the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to dealing with the crisis (what role central banks played in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another issue).
In a system using a flexible currency without intrinsic value, the quantity of money must change over time in order for the purchasing power of money to remain roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, central banks have taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; there is only the eternal mission that needs to be achieved.
If you find this assertion arrogant, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If the purchasing power of their money was severely damaged after 2008, they naturally would seek to exchange their currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other forms of savings).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, central banks in many countries have failed to meet inflation targets.
(Central banks usually define the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%.
) But this is certainly unpleasant, it does not lead to a disaster, especially considering that falling prices are partly due to supply — rather than demand — shocks, such as a sharp drop in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and does not threaten price stability, at least for net oil-importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this by increasing sales by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
Probably not.
After all, private companies' planned and actual profits and revenues often deviate by 10% or more.
Most businesses have fewer variables in their operating environments than central banks.
If that's the case, how can one expect central banks to always achieve precise inflation targets regardless of economic conditions?
It must be clarified that I am not saying central banks should not strive to work towards their targets.
They absolutely should do so.
Furthermore, they absolutely should not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
However, when evaluating central banks, people need to maintain proper restraint.
They do need to stop saying untrue things — for example, that the central bank's policy arsenal is not only possibly exhausted, but is already nearly exhausted.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal.
These weapons vary in caliber and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
But the ability of central banks to create and destroy money is theoretically unlimited.
Central bank governors should say "enough" to the criticism they face from ignorance.
None of our critics have been able to explain clearly and credibly why price stability is the wrong goal, what key objective central banks should pursue; and what entirely different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a very simple reason for this: the approach taken by central banks in developed countries since the crisis was the correct approach.
In fact, this approach pulled our economy back from the edge of the cliff.
You're welcome.
